original_question: When there is no mass in a volume of space, the space is not what?
diverse_qns: What is space not considered if it lacks mass entirely in a particular volume?
What term doesn't apply to the volume of space when it doesn't contain any mass?
When there's no mass present in a specific volume of space, what can't we call this space?
When dealing with a volume of space void of any mass, what description would not fit?
How wouldn't we describe a volume of space if it has no mass within it?
What phrase does not pertain to a volume of space that is free from mass?
If we have a volume of space devoid of mass, what attribute wouldn't be used to describe it?
When referring to a volume of space that has no mass, in what way wouldn't we describe it?
What wouldn't we say about volume of space lacking mass?
In the absence of mass in a volume of space, what term does not apply?
pred_diverse_ans: Space is considered empty or void if it lacks mass entirely in a particular volume.
The term "matter" doesn't apply to the volume of space when it doesn't contain any mass.
We cannot call this space a vacuum.
We would describe a volume of space with no mass within it as a vacuum.
"Vacuum" does not pertain to a volume of space that is free from mass.
We wouldn't describe it as a "massive" volume of space.
We would say that space is empty or has no matter.
